The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 Business Briefs

 New Delhi, July 10: The proposed strike by employees of public sector coal companies from July 18 has been called off by the five trade unions following an agreement with the Coal India Limited management on contentious issues relating to the finalisation of the National Coal Wage Agreement VII. The management of CIL and Singareni Coalfields Collieries Ltd and trade unions have amicably sorted out issues, including compassionate appointment, payment of arrears to coal workers of Bharat Coking Coal and Eastern Coalfields and minimum guaranteed benefit to workers.

 Mumbai, July 10: Foreign institutional investors recorded net purchases in equities at Rs 1,684.5 crore ($387 million) for the trading week ended July 8, while mutual funds were net sellers at Rs 203.54 crore.

 New Delhi, July 10: UTI Mutual Fund is planning a scheme which will allow a person to convert gold ornaments into tradable units and get a return on it.

 New Delhi, July 10: Finance minister P. Chidambaram has said the setting up of large taxpayer units, aimed at providing a single window for big assesses, will take at least six months.

 New Delhi, July 10: BSNL may have to take a hit worth Rs 8,000 crore if the proposed OneIndia concept of uniform calling rates across the country is introduced without alternate revenue sources.




